“It’s distressing,” said Madeline Cohen, a capital defense attorney who represents three inmates on federal death row.
It prompted President Barack Obama to call on the Justice Department to review the application of the death penalty nationwide.
Public support for the death penalty had hit a four-decade low in 2016, but it has slightly increased since, according to the Pew Research Center.
Technically, there is a defined and limited set of crimes that warrant the federal death penalty.
But Cohen, the federal capital defense attorney, says there is only one person on federal death row for a terrorism crime—the Boston Marathon bomber— and no one there for espionage.